Our game strategy aims to control as many junctions as possible and gain a circuit. Because this is a very dynamic game, our strategy changes mid-match, but generally our matches would start with gaining a circuit. We gather our initial cones from the left cone stack - because our autonomous period places us near there - to stay clear of our alliance partner. There are two types of circuits: offensive and defensive. The offensive circuit is used when we believe (through the circumstance of our alliance partner or the opposing alliance) that we are allowed to be more aggressive and limit our opponents' options more. The defensive circuit is used when we believe that our alliance partner can pressure the opposing alliance themselves or the opposing alliance can easily suppress our offensive plays. If our alliance partner is unable to score on low, medium or high junctions, we allow them to capture the two terminals we need for the circuit.

--You have some good ideas, but also some inaccurate reading of the lines which will weaken otherwise good work.
--Good thesis that you begin with.
--How did you conclude that "men's eyes" in the first quote were Claudius' eyes? The implication is that the deeds that will rise will be visible to ALL men's eyes. Hamlet even says this quote before he's seen the ghost.
--It was the actor who wept while presenting the scene from the play, not Hamlet. Hamlet was upset with himself for not having taken action yet. If the actor had such emotion from a fictional play, Hamlet chastises himself for not acting on something in real life.
--I don't see how you get from the "miraculous organ" to Claudius' eyes.
--Yes, Claudius' 'confession' may not be from speaking but from reacting. That's a powerful claim.
--So, don't panic on this early assignment. Do be careful that your claims are accurate so you can get full power in your writing.
